<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900504-0044</DOCNO><DOCID>900504-0044.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Reliance Group Holdings Inc.:   First-Period Net Fell 64%   On Revenue Increase of 8%</HL><DATE>05/04/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   REL</CO><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)</IN><LP>   Reliance Group Holdings Inc. said earnings declined 64% inthe first quarter primarily because of &quot;difficult marketconditions in some lines of business.&quot;   Profit fell to $9.6 million, or 13 cents a share, from$27.1 million, or 36 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenuerose 8% to $924.7 million from $854.9 million.</LP><TEXT>   Profit from property and casualty insurance operationsdropped 66% to $22.7 million from $67 million. New York-basedReliance blamed price competition and a decline in premiumswritten in 1990. However, income from life insurance as wellas title and mortgage insurance rose.   Reliance has reported that its $630 million sale of itsGeneral Casualty Insurance Co. subsidiary will result in a$380 million pretax gain in the second quarter.   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,Reliance closed at $5.625 a share, down 12.5 cents.   ---   Corrections andamp; Amplifications                                                                                                          RELIANCE GROUP HOLDINGS Inc. said first-quarter earningsdeclined primarily because of a large year-earlier gain fromthe sale of an equity investment. Yesterday's editionincorrectly attributed the drop mainly to market conditions.   (WSJ May 8, 1990)</TEXT></DOC>